<br>
This system is good and bad.  For some guilds, usually the higher end guilds, this system allows the chance to have a zone virtually all to their own, for both exp and raid kills.  However, for the other 80% of players on a server, this system means they will never see half the zones.  How many casual players will do the High Priest cycle in Crypt of Decay?  How many will see Temple of Marr?  How many will explore Solusek's Tower?  How many of these casual players will ever see the Elemental planes?<br>
<br>
I can understand what happened yesterday in PoI.  The frustration of being limited to 4 (or 6) zones because you dont have the time to put into the game (or just dont play as hard as some others) must be reaching the limits.  Sure, all expansions have those zones that some may never see.  For Kunark it was Veeshan's Peak.  For Velious, it was Sleeper's Tomb.  For Luclin, it was Vex Thal.  But for PoP, its not just 1 or 2 zones.  Its HoH-B, Sol Ro Tower, 4 Elemental Planes, Plane of Time.  Thats 7 zones and lots of gear and mobs that most players will never see!<br>
<br>
Imagine the frustration of knowing this.  Now, imagine what its like to know that if you race over to PoI and flag this NPC, you'll get access to Plane of Tactics, a new hunting ground, a new zone  just to see!  Even if thats as far as these players will get, its something new and exciting!!  Of course, utter pandemonium ensued at the factory in PoI, but thats human nature --- you can't blame em for that.<br>
<br>
Was it a mistake for the raid leader to invite everyone and their dog to hail the flag NPC?  Yes, I think it was.  It cheapens the kill, and as everyone saw, resulted in complete chaos.  This reminds me of something on the Drinal server:  The &quot;Flag Rebellion&quot; ,  a loose alliance of a number of guilds that get together and zerg boss mobs for flagging purposes.  I'm talking about hundreds of players getting flags just for the purpose of getting around SOE's implemented system.  And while the resident &quot;uber&quot; guild, Cats In Hats, doesn't mind so much (they even send their own players that have missed out on flags) it seems to be getting mixed results on the server population.  Some thing its a good thing, because it allows so many to see new zones.  However, those that have killed the boss mobs on their own feel this &quot;rebellion&quot; cheapens their own respective kills and gives players something for free, whereas they themselves worked hard for it.<br>
<br>
I dont want to be accused of libel with respect to the Empire Alliance here on Karana, but in my mind, this is what Empire does.  I dont see how Loot can be handled in any efficient way with 100+ members present at a boss kill that drops 3 items.  So, in my mind, Empire alliance members arent in it for the loot; rather they're in to see things dead and move on to the next thing.  Progression at the expense of upgrades.  I could be wrong, and if this offends any Empire alliance members, then please accept my apologies in advance.<br>
<br>
Anyway, you're right the PoP flag system sucks.  Really sucks.  If SOE doesnt fix it, or try to make it better for the players, then the players are going to go around it whenever possible.  This will most likely result in more incidents like yesterday's stampedes in PoI, but what can you do?  Players being left out of zones isnt a new thing, but 1-2 zones per expansion was a tolerable limit.  7+ zones in an expansion is ridiculous. <p><align=center><font face="Tahoma"><a 

